original_table_html:
Old logo New logo
HERSHEY'S The Hershey Company HERSHEY THE HERSHEY COMPANY
Pizza Hut (logo with red roof) Pizza Hut (red circle with white text)
SOUTHWEST (black capital letters with jet) Southwest (blue title case letters with heart icon)
IHOP (blue with red banner) IHOP (blue letters with red smile under "OP")
Google (multicolor serif font) Google (multicolor sans serif font)
G (one letter in four colors)
Four colored dots and microphone icon
summary_markdown: This table illustrates a comparative analysis of old and new logos for several prominent brands, highlighting design evolution. For HERSHEY'S, the transition moved from a more descriptive company name to a simplified brand name and company identifier. Pizza Hut shifted from a literal representation of its iconic red roof to a more abstract circular design with text. Southwest Airlines evolved from bold, all-caps lettering with a jet graphic to a softer, title-case font incorporating a heart symbol. IHOP's logo changed from a blue design with a red banner to a blue wordmark featuring a red smile element. Google underwent a significant transformation, moving from a multicolor serif font to a multicolor sans-serif font, and also introduced a single-letter "G" logo in four colors, alongside a favicon-like design of four colored dots and a microphone icon. The overall structure is comparative, showcasing the "before" and "after" of brand identity redesigns.
